I don't know the psychology behind transgenderism, so I apologize if I take a misstep here.

I don't think you're transgender. I think you're a guy who wants to be emotional. Everyone, and by that I mean everyone, has a certain amount of wanting to be vulnerable and intimate. Some people have a lot of it, others not so much. You happen to be a male (read: human being with a cock) who has those feminine tendencies. That's okay. You *do* have the need for gender roles to go away, because you're a more effeminate male, instead of the "emotionless, stoic, and plain" male. It might be that you've fallen victim to the collective trauma males have in which they're expected to be providers and not human beings with feelings and emotions, and you're overcompensating for that by wanting a lot of intimacy and vulnerability. All of this is okay.

What's not okay, on the other hand, is changing who you are, whether it's physical or cognitive/mentally or even hormonally because the world around you doesn't accept the way you are. If you want to start dealing with this, accept yourself the way you are, and start acting like it. If there's others that reject you for being who you are, then you should reject them for not letting you be who you want to be. Because after all, it's the 'you' who you feel comfortable with, right?

Once you're comfortable with yourself, in- and outside and all, then you'll be able to add other people to your life who will appreciate you for who you are.

If you genuinely feel you're a *woman*, i.e. you're not an effeminate male, then by all means transition. But make sure you understand the difference and which one you are *very* carefully before you try to change who you are into something you might not want to be.

That's my two cents. I hope they're of value to you.

Goal of the thread: Treat yourself to something nice, be it a meal, a hot bath, or something else you'd enjoy doing.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

I ask myself the same thing. Part of it, I think, is the Internet creating the possibility for people with a set of symptoms and/or feelings to discover each other and share knowledge of what works best for their condition. This seems entirely benign.

There might be a bit of that going on too: situations where vague feelings of inadequacy get confused for gender dysphoria and then this idea is continuously reinforced through participation in online communities for gender dysphoric people. I guess one could make the case that, if these non-dysphoric people were to become a majority in gender dysphoric communities the meaning of transness would evolve and expand significantly.

Whatever it might be, I agree that it's entirely undeniable that the Internet has shaped the current trans movement to a large degree; but then, the Internet has been a transformative force in practically all facets of human life. That's were trans issues get tied with transhumanism, I think.

It sounds like you're squeezing your throat and you're using too much weight in your voice, both of which can lead to strain. basic steps:
1: learn how to control your larynx. The issue is that you aren't used to using the muscles consciously, so you need some kind of shortcut to teach your brain how to use them. Examples are this: http://lena.kiev.ua/voice/ and this: https://www.reddit.com/r/transvoice/comments/7r5ekb/lookin_for_some_larynx_lift_clarification/dsuomke/
There are more out there, but they all teach the same thing, so keep trying until you get one that works. This will increase your voice's resonance, but it'll take months of regular use before it stops sounding forced and unnatural and becomes something you can do for a sustained period of time.
2: practice for months. The easiest way is to do it in conversation with other people. Your biggest obstacle here is burnout, and conversations solve this by keeping you from getting bored and keeping you from listening to the sound of your cringe unpracticed trannyvoice for hours at a time. >>29319362
Warm shower or a hot washcloth on the face to help soften the hairs.

Use a hypoallergenic conditioner + a shave brush to lather it on your face. Conditioner works better than any shave cream, gel or soap. Make sure you use enough water with it so its not too thick or dry.

Let conditioner sit on facial hairs for a couple of minutes to soften them before you start shaving.

If you can only shave with the grain, get a safety razor and use Feather blades. If your skin can tolerate shaving against the grain, get a Mach 3. Either way, learn to use very little pressure and learn how to pull your skin taught as its taught for people using safety razors.

Rinse your blade frequently with hot water.

Be most careful around your upper lip and chin, they tend to be the easiest areas to irritate your skin and/or nick yourself.

Rinse with cool/cold water, pat try with towel, moisturize shaved areas very well.
